<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-103-276  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 103 276.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  March 6 1989 v8 n5 p66(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>There's no prize for Blue Ribbon follow-through. (Blue RibbonCommission on Defense Management)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schwartz, Karen D.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Most of the recommendations made by the Blue Ribbon Commission onDefense Management, commonly known as the Packard Commission afterCommission Chmn David Packard of HP, have been implemented by theDepartment of Defense (DOD), but a recent report says not all ofthe recommendations have been completely carried out.andP;  The report,'Status of Recommendations by Blue Ribbon Commission on DefenseManagement,' says the DOD has begun to reform its acquisitionprocedures, but has not created top-level acquisition posts asrecommended.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Department of DefenseUnited States. Presidential Commission on Defense ManagementGovernment Regulation.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>There's No Prize for Blue Ribbon Follow-ThroughandM;The Defense Department has implemented many of the recommendations made bythe Blue Ribbon Commission on Defense Management, but some recommendedimprovements -- such as the creation of top-level acquisition posts -- havenot been carried out completely, according to a recent report.andM;The report, Status of Recommendations by Blue Ribbon Commission on DefenseManagement, was prepared by the General Accounting Office for Sen.andP;  WilliamV. Roth Jr.andP;  (R-Del.).andP;  The Blue Ribbon Commission is commonly known as thePackard Commission.andM;DOD has made some progress in reforming its acquisition procedures, thereport said.andM;The commission had recommended the creation of the office of undersecretaryfor acquisition to supervise the performance of the entire acquisition systemand set policy for research and development, testing, logistics andprocurement.andM;DOD officials created the position in November 1986, but in a July 1987report, the commission's David Packard told then-President Reagan theposition was ineffective and not what the commission had envisioned.andM;Other acquisition-related recommendations included creation of serviceacquisition executives (SAEs) and program executive officers.andP;  The serviceswere to appoint SAEs at the undersecretary level.andP;  The SAEs would beresponsible for administering service acquisition programs.andM;Each SAE then was to appoint program executive officers, who would handle adefined number of acquisition programs.andM;In the Army and Navy, the undersecretary was appointed SAE.andM;In the Air Force, the assistant secretary for acquisition received theadditional title of SAE.andM;The report said the Air Force SAE was not equal in rank to an undersecretaryand was not a full-time SAE.andP;  The Army and Navy SAEs had many other dutiesunrelated to their service acquisition executive role, the report said.andM;The final set of recommendations regarding defense acquisition concernedcommercial goods and services.andP;  The commission recommended that thegovernment make a sincere attempt to use off-the-shelf components, systemsand services.andM;Rather than relying on rigid military specifications, the report said, DODshould make greater use of existing commercial goods and services, turning tonew or custom-made items only as a last resort.andM;DOD revised its regulations to encourage greater use of ready-made items.andP;  ADefense Federal Acquisition Regulation encouraging the use of commercialproducts was issued last year.andO;</TEXT></DOC>